<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1876&amp;p=16072#p16072</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1876&amp;p=16072#p16072"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Something I changed..]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1876&amp;p=16072#p16072"><![CDATA[
I would also suggest (somewhat hypocritically) that once you find the source of your bug, write a unit test to reproduce the behavior.  That way once you've found a bug and written a test for it, you almost guarantee that the bug will not ever re-introduce itself without being flagged as a unit test failure.<br />I started writing a emulator using this method after reading Kent Beck's "Test-Driven Development" book.  I think it's a fantastic idea, however I did have some trouble with the implementation.  I think I ended up with very tightly coupled code/tests.<br />I would also ditto Tepples suggestion that using revision control is probably better than doing it manually with zip files.  But whatever works best for you is what you should stick with <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /> I like Subversion quite a bit personally.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=29">teaguecl</a> — Tue Aug 08, 2006 11:12 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
